<doc id="490135" wikidata="Q5891416" url="?curid=490135" title="Homological conjectures in commutative algebra">
<text>In mathematics, homological conjectures have been a focus of research activity in commutative algebra since the early 1960s. They concern a number of interrelated (sometimes surprisingly so) conjectures relating various homological properties of a commutative ring to its internal ring structure, particularly its Krull dimension and depth.

The following list given by Melvin Hochster is considered definitive for this area. In the sequel, formula_1, and formula_2 refer to Noetherian commutative rings; formula_3 will be a local ring with maximal ideal formula_4, and formula_5 and formula_6 are finitely generated formula_3-modules.

# The Zero Divisor Theorem. If formula_8 has finite projective dimension and formula_9 is not a zero divisor on formula_5, then formula_11 is not a zero divisor on formula_3.
# Bass&#x27;s Question. If formula_8 has a finite injective resolution then formula_3 is a Cohen–Macaulay ring.
# The Intersection Theorem. If formula_15 has finite length, then the Krull dimension of &quot;N&quot; (i.e., the dimension of &quot;R&quot; modulo the annihilator of &quot;N&quot;) is at most the projective dimension of &quot;M&quot;.
# The New Intersection Theorem. Let formula_16 denote a finite complex of free &quot;R&quot;-modules such that formula_17 has finite length but is not 0. Then the (Krull dimension) formula_18.
# The Improved New Intersection Conjecture. Let formula_16 denote a finite complex of free &quot;R&quot;-modules such that formula_20 has finite length for formula_21 and formula_22 has a minimal generator that is killed by a power of the maximal ideal of &quot;R&quot;. Then formula_18.
# The Direct Summand Conjecture. If formula_24 is a module-finite ring extension with &quot;R&quot; regular (here, &quot;R&quot; need not be local but the problem reduces at once to the local case), then &quot;R&quot; is a direct summand of &quot;S&quot; as an &quot;R&quot;-module. The conjecture was proven by Yves André using a theory of perfectoid spaces.
# The Canonical Element Conjecture. Let formula_25 be a system of parameters for &quot;R&quot;, let formula_26 be a free &quot;R&quot;-resolution of the residue field of &quot;R&quot; with formula_27, and let formula_28 denote the Koszul complex of &quot;R&quot; with respect to formula_25. Lift the identity map formula_30 to a map of complexes. Then no matter what the choice of system of parameters or lifting, the last map from formula_31 is not 0.
# Existence of Balanced Big Cohen–Macaulay Modules Conjecture. There exists a (not necessarily finitely generated) &quot;R&quot;-module &quot;W&quot; such that &quot;mRW ≠ W&quot; and every system of parameters for &quot;R&quot; is a regular sequence on &quot;W&quot;.
# Cohen-Macaulayness of Direct Summands Conjecture. If &quot;R&quot; is a direct summand of a regular ring &quot;S&quot; as an &quot;R&quot;-module, then &quot;R&quot; is Cohen–Macaulay (&quot;R&quot; need not be local, but the result reduces at once to the case where &quot;R&quot; is local).
# The Vanishing Conjecture for Maps of Tor. Let formula_32 be homomorphisms where &quot;R&quot; is not necessarily local (one can reduce to that case however), with &quot;A, S&quot; regular and &quot;R&quot; finitely generated as an &quot;A&quot;-module. Let &quot;W&quot; be any &quot;A&quot;-module. Then the map formula_33 is zero for all formula_34.
# The Strong Direct Summand Conjecture. Let formula_24 be a map of complete local domains, and let &quot;Q&quot; be a height one prime ideal of &quot;S&quot; lying over formula_36, where &quot;R&quot; and formula_37 are both regular. Then formula_36 is a direct summand of &quot;Q&quot; considered as &quot;R&quot;-modules.
# Existence of Weakly Functorial Big Cohen-Macaulay Algebras Conjecture. Let formula_39 be a local homomorphism of complete local domains. Then there exists an &quot;R&quot;-algebra &quot;BR&quot; that is a balanced big Cohen–Macaulay algebra for &quot;R&quot;, an &quot;S&quot;-algebra formula_40 that is a balanced big Cohen-Macaulay algebra for &quot;S&quot;, and a homomorphism &quot;BR → BS&quot; such that the natural square given by these maps commutes.
# Serre&#x27;s Conjecture on Multiplicities. (cf. [[Serre&#x27;s multiplicity conjectures]].) Suppose that &quot;R&quot; is regular of dimension &quot;d&quot; and that formula_41 has finite length. Then formula_42, defined as the alternating sum of the lengths of the modules formula_43 is 0 if formula_44, and is positive if the sum is equal to &quot;d&quot;. (N.B. Jean-Pierre Serre proved that the sum cannot exceed &quot;d&quot;.)
# Small Cohen–Macaulay Modules Conjecture. If &quot;R&quot; is complete, then there exists a finitely-generated &quot;R&quot;-module formula_8 such that some (equivalently every) system of parameters for &quot;R&quot; is a regular sequence on &quot;M&quot;.

==References==

* Homological conjectures, old and new, Melvin Hochster, Illinois Journal of Mathematics Volume 51, Number 1 (2007), 151-169.
* On the direct summand conjecture and its derived variant by Bhargav Bhatt.</text><links>
